---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '@/components/Breadcrumb.astro';

const revised = '2026-03-28';
---

<BaseLayout title="Versioning & Canonical Status" description="How the APS Publishing Platform tracks content versions and canonical status.">
  <div class="content-wrapper">
    <Breadcrumb items={[{ label: 'Platform and Policies' }, { label: 'Versioning & Canonical Status' }]} />

    <header class="page-header">
      <h1>Versioning &amp; Canonical Status</h1>
      <div class="page-revised">Revised: {revised}</div>
    </header>

    <div class="article-body">
      <p>
        The APS Publishing Platform distinguishes between different stages of content development.
      </p>

      <h2>Canonical</h2>
      <p>
        Canonical pages represent the stable, authoritative core of the APS framework. These pages
        have been reviewed and are considered conceptually settled. Changes to canonical content are
        controlled and tracked through revision dates.
      </p>

      <h2>Evolving</h2>
      <p>
        Evolving pages are under active development. They may be refined, expanded, or reorganised
        as the framework progresses.
      </p>

      <h2>Draft</h2>
      <p>Draft pages are provisional and may undergo substantial revision.</p>

      <h2>Revision Tracking</h2>
      <p>
        All pages include a "Revised" date indicating the most recent update. This ensures that
        citations and references can be tied to a specific version of the content.
      </p>

      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>Versioning supports:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>transparency in development</li>
        <li>stability of core concepts</li>
        <li>ongoing refinement without loss of continuity</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        This system allows APS to function as a living but disciplined body of work.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
